<br>
Firstly I actually agree with the government policies of the mid 60's to late 1970's that there should be alternatives to fossil fuels, particularly oil. They recognised that oil was a finite resource and that the primary source of the oil - the middle east - was unstable &amp; OPEC was well underway. In addition to North Sea exploration(or exploitation) they also began to build nuclear power stations.<br>
<br>
As far as I'm aware - I'm not that well read on Sellafield - this station was set up primarily as a means of processing the spent fuel from the other reactors around the UK. In fairness then - it's perhaps no surprise that it's costing money to run.<br>
<br>
I think now the days of nuclear fuel are over, and that there are much better alternatives to oil, which are safer. I also firmly believe that Greenpeace and the other pressure groups are misunderstanding this whole issue. Nuclear waste processing is big business - but its also very neccesary. Protesting against the reprocessing of this waste doesn't really make sense. In fact I'd rather have the stuff processed here because I believe its safer. Okay the recent case was unfortunate - but thats how these sensitive issues go. I'd rather have a well protected ship, then a very very big environmental disaster.<br>
<br>
So what should happen? Well I'm afraid I think nothing. The UK needs a reprocessing facility and with the closure of Torness(near Wick, North coast of Scotland) the only viable plant is Sellafield. I'm aware of the environmental concerns but I'm quietly(perhaps foolishly)trusting that these issues are now sorted. It's surely not making a mess of the Irish sea anymore?<br>
<br>
Perhaps we need a public investigation, but guess what, that will cost millions too.  <br>
<br>
You can't change the past, only influence the future. Sign petitions for green fuels instead.<br>
<br>
Good topic. My apologies for taking so long to respond.<br>
<br>
